<hl>
<seg id=1> China to continue to open up its financial policy to the outside world </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Beijing, Jan. 16 (Xinhua News Agency) Dai Xianglong the President of the People's Bank of China said that, China was to maintain its open financial policies. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Mr. Dai Xianglong said at the news conference held here today, that China will not give up its open financial policies for the financial turbulence taking place in some Southeast Asian countries. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> He said that, there were a number of foreign banks and insurance companies established branches in China. By the end of the year, there had been over 170 foreign funded commercial financial institutions that opened business in China. </seg>
<seg id=5> In the future, a reasonable number of foreign banks and insurance companies will be encouraged to establish branches in China, and the People's Bank of China is ready to experiment on expanding their business scope with Renminbi transactions. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Meanwhile, he emphasized that, the applications of the foreign financial institutions to open business in China will be more carefully administered on relevant circumstances, qualification of the high executives and the legality of the transactions to be done. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He said that, there is no timetable for realizing full convertibility of Renminbi in the capital account in the first place. Therefore, there's no such question that China will put off this process because of the Southeast Asia Financial Crisis. </seg>
<seg id=8> Taking the lesson of Southeast Asia Financial Crisis, China will adopt a more prudent attitude upon the opening of the capital account. </seg>
</p>
